04991nam a22007095i 9780748632176DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20222010stk    fo  d z      eng d  a97807486321767 a10.1515/97807486321762doi  a(DE-B1597)614270  a(OCoLC)1302166068  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  astkcGB-SCT 7aHIS0150002bisacsh04a942.8032221 aHolford, Matthew, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBorder Liberties and Loyalties :bNorth-East England, c. 1200 to c. 1400 /cMatthew Holford, Keith Stringer. 1aEdinburgh : bEdinburgh University Press, c[2022] 4c©2010  a1 online resource (480 p.) :b6 Maps  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tMaps and Tables -- tPreface -- tAuthors’ Notes -- tAbbreviations -- tManuscript and Record Sources -- tMap 1 The Greater Liberties of North-East England -- tIntroduction -- tPART I THE ECCLESIASTICAL LIBERTIES -- t1 Durham: History, Culture and Identity -- t2 Durham: Government, Administration and the Local Community -- t3 Durham: Patronage, Service and Good Lordship -- t4 Durham under Bishop Anthony Bek, 1283–1311 -- t5 Hexhamshire and Tynemouthshire -- tPART II THE SECULAR LIBERTIES -- t6 Tynedale: Power, Society and Identities, c. 1200–1296 -- t7 Tynedale: A Community in Transition, 1296–c. 1400 -- t8 Redesdale -- tConclusions and Wider Perspectives -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aGBS_insertPreviewButtonPopup('ISBN:9780748632787);This book examines the organisation of power and society in north-east England over two crucial centuries in the emergence of the English 'state'. England is usually regarded as medieval Europe's most centralised kingdom, yet the North-East was dominated by liberties - largely self-governing jurisdictions - that greatly restricted the English crown's direct authority in the region. These local polities receive here their first comprehensive discussion; and their histories are crucial for understanding questions of state-formation in frontier zones, regional distinctiveness, and local and national loyalties.The analysis focuses on liberties as both governmental entities and sources of socio-political and cultural identification. It also connects the development of liberties and their communities with a rich variety of forces, including the influence of the kings of Scots as lords of Tynedale, and the impact of protracted Anglo-Scottish warfare from 1296. Why did liberties enjoy such long-term relevance as governance structures? How far, and why, did the English monarchy respect their autonomous rights and status? By what means, and how successfully, were liberty identities created, sharpened and sustained? In addressing such issues, this ground-breaking study extends beyond regional history to make significant contributions to the ongoing mainstream debates about 'state', 'society', 'identity' and 'community'."  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aState-local relationsxHistoryxTo 1500xEngland. 0aState-local relationszEnglandxHistoryyTo 1500. 4aHistory. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Great Britain / General.2bisacsh1 aHolford, Matthew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStringer, Keith, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aStringer, Keith, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEdinburgh University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2013-2000z97831107804680 cprintz978074863278740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978074863217640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780748632176423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780748632176/original  a978-3-11-078046-8  E